#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/the_basics.md:1
msgid "The basics"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/the_basics.md:3
msgid "Foundational knowledge on using and configuring Black."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/the_basics.md:5
msgid "_Black_ is a well-behaved Unix-style command-line tool:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/the_basics.md:7
msgid "it does nothing if it finds no sources to format;"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/the_basics.md:8
msgid ""
"it will read from standard input and write to standard output if `-` is used "
"as the filename;"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/the_basics.md:10
msgid "it only outputs messages to users on standard error;"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/the_basics.md:11
msgid ""
"exits with code 0 unless an internal error occurred or a CLI option prompted "
"it."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/the_basics.md:13
msgid "Usage"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/the_basics.md:15
msgid ""
"_Black_ will reformat entire files in place. To get started right away with "
"sensible defaults:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/the_basics.md:18
msgid "black {source_file_or_directory}\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/the_basics.md:22
msgid ""
"You can run _Black_ as a package if running it as a script doesn't work:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/the_basics.md:24
msgid "python -m black {source_file_or_directory}\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/the_basics.md:28
msgid "Ignoring sections"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/the_basics.md:30
msgid ""
"Black will not reformat lines that contain `# fmt: skip` or blocks that "
"start with `# fmt: off` and end with `# fmt: on`. `# fmt: skip` can be mixed "
"with other pragmas/comments either with multiple comments (e.g. `# fmt: skip "
"# pylint # noqa`) or as a semicolon separated list (e.g. `# fmt: skip; "
"pylint; noqa`). `# fmt: on/off` must be on the same level of indentation and "
"in the same block, meaning no unindents beyond the initial indentation level "
"between them. Black also recognizes [YAPF](https://github.com/google/yapf)'s "
"block comments to the same effect, as a courtesy for straddling code."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/the_basics.md:39
msgid "Command line options"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/the_basics.md:41
msgid ""
"The CLI options of _Black_ can be displayed by running `black --help`. All "
"options are also covered in more detail below."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/the_basics.md:44
msgid ""
"While _Black_ has quite a few knobs these days, it is still opinionated so "
"style options are deliberately limited and rarely added."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/the_basics.md:47
msgid ""
"Note that all command-line options listed above can also be configured using "
"a `pyproject.toml` file (more on that below)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/the_basics.md:50
msgid "`-h`, `--help`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/the_basics.md:52
msgid "Show available command-line options and exit."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/the_basics.md:54
msgid "`-c`, `--code`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/the_basics.md:56
msgid "Format the code passed in as a string."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/the_basics.md:58
msgid ""
"$ black --code \"print ( 'hello, world' )\"\n"
"print(\"hello, world\")\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/the_basics.md:63
msgid "`-l`, `--line-length`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/the_basics.md:65
msgid "How many characters per line to allow. The default is 88."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/the_basics.md:67
msgid "See also [the style documentation](labels/line-length)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/the_basics.md:69
msgid "`-t`, `--target-version`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/the_basics.md:71
msgid ""
"Python versions that should be supported by Black's output. You can run "
"`black --help` and look for the `--target-version` option to see the full "
"list of supported versions. You should include all versions that your code "
"supports. If you support Python 3.11 through 3.13, you should write:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/the_basics.md:76
msgid "$ black -t py311 -t py312 -t py313\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/the_basics.md:80
msgid "In a [configuration file](#configuration-via-a-file), you can write:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/the_basics.md:82
msgid "target-version = [\"py311\", \"py312\", \"py313\"]\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/the_basics.md:86
msgid ""
"By default, Black will infer target versions from the project metadata in "
"`pyproject.toml`, specifically the `[project.requires-python]` field. If "
"this does not yield conclusive results, Black will use per-file auto-"
"detection."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/the_basics.md:90
msgid ""
"_Black_ uses this option to decide what grammar to use to parse your code. "
"In addition, it may use it to decide what style to use. For example, support "
"for a trailing comma after `*args` in a function call was added in Python "
"3.5, so _Black_ will add this comma only if the target versions are all "
"Python 3.5 or higher:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/the_basics.md:95
msgid ""
"$ black --line-length=10 --target-version=py35 -c 'f(a, *args)'\n"
"f(\n"
"    a,\n"
"    *args,\n"
")\n"
"$ black --line-length=10 --target-version=py34 -c 'f(a, *args)'\n"
"f(\n"
"    a,\n"
"    *args\n"
")\n"
"$ black --line-length=10 --target-version=py34 --target-version=py35 -c "
"'f(a, *args)'\n"
"f(\n"
"    a,\n"
"    *args\n"
")\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/the_basics.md:113
msgid "`--pyi`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/the_basics.md:115
msgid ""
"Format all input files like typing stubs regardless of file extension. This "
"is useful when piping source on standard input."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/the_basics.md:118
msgid "`--ipynb`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/the_basics.md:120
msgid ""
"Format all input files like Jupyter Notebooks regardless of file extension. "
"This is useful when piping source on standard input."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/the_basics.md:123
msgid "`--python-cell-magics`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/the_basics.md:125
msgid ""
"When processing Jupyter Notebooks, add the given magic to the list of known "
"python- magics. Useful for formatting cells with custom python magics. See "
"the [Jupyter Notebooks guide](../guides/using_black_with_jupyter_notebooks."
"md) for more details."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/the_basics.md:130
msgid "`-x, --skip-source-first-line`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/the_basics.md:132
msgid "Skip the first line of the source code."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/the_basics.md:134
msgid "`-S, --skip-string-normalization`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/the_basics.md:136
msgid ""
"By default, _Black_ uses double quotes for all strings and normalizes string "
"prefixes, as described in [the style documentation](labels/strings). If this "
"option is given, strings are left unchanged instead."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/the_basics.md:140
msgid "`-C, --skip-magic-trailing-comma`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/the_basics.md:142
msgid ""
"By default, _Black_ uses existing trailing commas as an indication that "
"short lines should be left separate, as described in [the style "
"documentation](labels/magic-trailing-comma). If this option is given, the "
"magic trailing comma is ignored."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/the_basics.md:147
msgid "`--preview`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/the_basics.md:149
msgid ""
"Enable potentially disruptive style changes that we expect to add to Black's "
"main functionality in the next major release. Use this if you want a taste "
"of what next year's style will look like."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/the_basics.md:153
msgid "Read more about [our preview style](labels/preview-style)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/the_basics.md:155
#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/the_basics.md:164
msgid ""
"There is no guarantee on the code style produced by this flag across "
"releases."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/the_basics.md:157
msgid "`--unstable`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/the_basics.md:159
msgid ""
"Enable all style changes in `--preview`, plus additional changes that we "
"would like to make eventually, but that have known issues that need to be "
"fixed before they can move back to the `--preview` style. Use this if you "
"want to experiment with these changes and help fix issues with them."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/the_basics.md:166
msgid "`--enable-unstable-feature`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/the_basics.md:168
msgid ""
"Enable specific features from the `--unstable` style. See [the preview style "
"documentation](labels/unstable-features) for the list of supported features. "
"This flag can only be used when `--preview` is enabled. Users are encouraged "
"to use this flag if they use `--preview` style and a feature that affects "
"their code is moved from the `--preview` to the `--unstable` style, but they "
"want to avoid the thrash from undoing this change."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/the_basics.md:175
msgid ""
"There are no guarantees on the behavior of these features, or even their "
"existence, across releases."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/the_basics.md:180
msgid "`--check`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/the_basics.md:182
msgid ""
"Don't write the files back, just return the status. _Black_ will exit with:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/the_basics.md:184
msgid "code 0 if nothing would change;"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/the_basics.md:185
msgid "code 1 if some files would be reformatted; or"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/the_basics.md:186
msgid "code 123 if there was an internal error"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/the_basics.md:188
msgid ""
"If used in combination with `--quiet` then only the exit code will be "
"returned, unless there was an internal error."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/the_basics.md:191
msgid ""
"$ black test.py --check\n"
"All done! ✨ 🍰 ✨\n"
"1 file would be left unchanged.\n"
"$ echo $?\n"
"0\n"
"\n"
"$ black test.py --check\n"
"would reformat test.py\n"
"Oh no! 💥 💔 💥\n"
"1 file would be reformatted.\n"
"$ echo $?\n"
"1\n"
"\n"
"$ black test.py --check\n"
"error: cannot format test.py: INTERNAL ERROR: Black produced code that is "
"not equivalent to the source.  Please report a bug on https://github.com/psf/"
"black/issues.  This diff might be helpful: /tmp/blk_kjdr1oog.log\n"
"Oh no! 💥 💔 💥\n"
"1 file would fail to reformat.\n"
"$ echo $?\n"
"123\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/the_basics.md:213
msgid "`--diff`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/the_basics.md:215
msgid ""
"Don't write the files back, just output a diff to indicate what changes "
"_Black_ would've made. They are printed to stdout so capturing them is "
"simple."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/the_basics.md:218
msgid "If you'd like colored diffs, you can enable them with `--color`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/the_basics.md:220
msgid ""
"$ black test.py --diff\n"
"--- test.py     2021-03-08 22:23:40.848954+00:00\n"
"+++ test.py     2021-03-08 22:23:47.126319+00:00\n"
"@@ -1 +1 @@\n"
"-print ( 'hello, world' )\n"
"+print(\"hello, world\")\n"
"would reformat test.py\n"
"All done! ✨ 🍰 ✨\n"
"1 file would be reformatted.\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/the_basics.md:232
msgid "`--no-cache`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/the_basics.md:234
msgid ""
"Do not consult or update Black's per-user cache during this run. When `--no-"
"cache` is specified, Black will perform fresh analysis for all files and "
"will neither read from nor write to the cache. This is helpful for "
"reproducing formatting results from a clean run, debugging cache-related "
"issues, or ensuring CI executes a fresh formatting analysis every time."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/the_basics.md:240
msgid "`--color` / `--no-color`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/the_basics.md:242
msgid ""
"Show (or do not show) colored diff. Only applies when `--diff` is given."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/the_basics.md:244
msgid "`--line-ranges`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/the_basics.md:246
msgid "When specified, _Black_ will try its best to only format these lines."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/the_basics.md:248
msgid ""
"This option can be specified multiple times, and a union of the lines will "
"be formatted. Each range must be specified as two integers connected by a `-"
"`: `<START>-<END>`. The `<START>` and `<END>` integer indices are 1-based "
"and inclusive on both ends."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/the_basics.md:252
msgid ""
"_Black_ may still format lines outside of the ranges for multi-line "
"statements. Formatting more than one file or any Jupyter Notebooks with this "
"option is not supported. This option cannot be specified in the `pyproject."
"toml` config."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/the_basics.md:256
msgid ""
"Example: `black --line-ranges=1-10 --line-ranges=21-30 test.py` will format "
"lines from `1` to `10` and `21` to `30`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/the_basics.md:259
msgid ""
"This option is mainly for editor integrations, such as \"Format Selection\"."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/the_basics.md:262
msgid ""
"Due to [#4052](https://github.com/psf/black/issues/4052), `--line-ranges` "
"might format extra lines outside of the ranges when there are unformatted "
"lines with the exact formatted content next to the requested lines. It also "
"disables _Black_'s formatting stability check in `--safe` mode."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/the_basics.md:268
msgid "`--fast` / `--safe`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/the_basics.md:270
msgid ""
"By default, _Black_ performs [an AST safety check](labels/ast-changes) after "
"formatting your code. The `--fast` flag turns off this check and the `--"
"safe` flag explicitly enables it."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/the_basics.md:274
msgid "`--required-version`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/the_basics.md:276
msgid ""
"Require a specific version of _Black_ to be running. This is useful for "
"ensuring that all contributors to your project are using the same version, "
"because different versions of _Black_ may format code a little differently. "
"This option can be set in a configuration file for consistent results across "
"environments."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/the_basics.md:281
msgid ""
"$ black --version\n"
"black, 26.5.1 (compiled: yes)\n"
"$ black --required-version 26.5.1 -c \"format = 'this'\"\n"
"format = \"this\"\n"
"$ black --required-version 31.5b2 -c \"still = 'beta?!'\"\n"
"Oh no! 💥 💔 💥 The required version does not match the running version!\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/the_basics.md:290
msgid "You can also pass just the major version:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/the_basics.md:292
msgid ""
"$ black --required-version 22 -c \"format = 'this'\"\n"
"format = \"this\"\n"
"$ black --required-version 31 -c \"still = 'beta?!'\"\n"
"Oh no! 💥 💔 💥 The required version does not match the running version!\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/the_basics.md:299
msgid ""
"Because of our [stability policy](../the_black_code_style/index.md), this "
"will guarantee stable formatting, but still allow you to take advantage of "
"improvements that do not affect formatting."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/the_basics.md:303
msgid "`--exclude`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/the_basics.md:305
msgid ""
"A regular expression that matches files and directories that should be "
"excluded on recursive searches. An empty value means no paths are excluded. "
"Use forward slashes for directories on all platforms (Windows, too). By "
"default, Black also ignores all paths listed in `.gitignore`. Changing this "
"value will override all default exclusions."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/the_basics.md:310
msgid ""
"Default Exclusions: `['.direnv', '.eggs', '.git', '.hg', '."
"ipynb_checkpoints',  '.mypy_cache', '.nox', '.pytest_cache', '.ruff_cache', "
"'.tox', '.svn', '.venv', '.vscode',  '__pypackages__', '_build', 'buck-out', "
"'build', 'dist', 'venv'] `"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/the_basics.md:313
msgid ""
"If the regular expression contains newlines, it is treated as a [verbose "
"regular expression](https://docs.python.org/3/library/re.html#re.VERBOSE). "
"This is typically useful when setting these options in a `pyproject.toml` "
"configuration file; see [Configuration format](#configuration-format) for "
"more information."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/the_basics.md:318
msgid "`--extend-exclude`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/the_basics.md:320
msgid ""
"Like `--exclude`, but adds additional files and directories on top of the "
"default values instead of overriding them."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/the_basics.md:323
msgid "`--force-exclude`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/the_basics.md:325
msgid ""
"Like `--exclude`, but files and directories matching this regex will be "
"excluded even when they are passed explicitly as arguments. This is useful "
"when invoking Black programmatically on changed files, such as in a pre-"
"commit hook or editor plugin."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/the_basics.md:329
msgid "`--stdin-filename`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/the_basics.md:331
msgid ""
"The name of the file when passing it through stdin. Useful to make sure "
"Black will respect the `--force-exclude` option on some editors that rely on "
"using stdin."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/the_basics.md:334
msgid "`--include`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/the_basics.md:336
msgid ""
"A regular expression that matches files and directories that should be "
"included on recursive searches. An empty value means all files are included "
"regardless of the name. Use forward slashes for directories on all platforms "
"(Windows, too). Overrides all exclusions, including from `.gitignore` and "
"command line options."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/the_basics.md:341
msgid "Default Inclusions: `['.pyi', '.ipynb']`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/the_basics.md:343
msgid "`-W`, `--workers`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/the_basics.md:345
msgid ""
"When _Black_ formats multiple files, it may use a process pool to speed up "
"formatting. This option controls the number of parallel workers. This can "
"also be specified via the `BLACK_NUM_WORKERS` environment variable. Defaults "
"to the number of CPUs in the system."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/the_basics.md:349
msgid "`-q`, `--quiet`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/the_basics.md:351
msgid ""
"Stop emitting all non-critical output. Error messages will still be emitted "
"(which can silenced by `2>/dev/null`)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/the_basics.md:354
msgid ""
"$ black src/ -q\n"
"error: cannot format src/black_primer/cli.py: Cannot parse: 5:6\n"
"    mport asyncio\n"
"         ^\n"
"ParseError: bad input\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/the_basics.md:362
msgid "`-v`, `--verbose`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/the_basics.md:364
msgid ""
"Emit messages about files that were not changed or were ignored due to "
"exclusion patterns. If _Black_ is using a configuration file, a message "
"detailing which one it is using will be emitted."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/the_basics.md:368
msgid ""
"$ black src/ -v\n"
"Using configuration from /tmp/pyproject.toml.\n"
"src/blib2to3 ignored: matches the --extend-exclude regular expression\n"
"src/_black_version.py wasn't modified on disk since last run.\n"
"src/black/__main__.py wasn't modified on disk since last run.\n"
"error: cannot format src/black_primer/cli.py: Cannot parse: 5:6\n"
"    mport asyncio\n"
"         ^\n"
"ParseError: bad input\n"
"reformatted src/black_primer/lib.py\n"
"reformatted src/blackd/__init__.py\n"
"reformatted src/black/__init__.py\n"
"Oh no! 💥 💔 💥\n"
"3 files reformatted, 2 files left unchanged, 1 file failed to reformat\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/the_basics.md:385
msgid "`--version`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/the_basics.md:387
msgid ""
"You can check the version of _Black_ you have installed using the `--"
"version` flag."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/the_basics.md:389
msgid ""
"$ black --version\n"
"black, 26.5.1\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/the_basics.md:394
msgid "`--config`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/the_basics.md:396
msgid ""
"Read configuration options from a configuration file. See [below]"
"(#configuration-via-a-file) for more details on the configuration file."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/the_basics.md:399
msgid "Environment variable options"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/the_basics.md:401
msgid "_Black_ supports the following configuration via environment variables."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/the_basics.md:403
msgid "`BLACK_CACHE_DIR`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/the_basics.md:405
msgid "The directory where _Black_ should store its cache."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/the_basics.md:407
msgid "`BLACK_NUM_WORKERS`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/the_basics.md:409
msgid ""
"The number of parallel workers _Black_ should use. The command line option `-"
"W` / `--workers` takes precedence over this environment variable."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/the_basics.md:412
msgid "Code input alternatives"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/the_basics.md:414
msgid ""
"_Black_ supports formatting code via stdin, with the result being printed to "
"stdout. Just let _Black_ know with `-` as the path."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/the_basics.md:417
msgid ""
"$ echo \"print ( 'hello, world' )\" | black -\n"
"print(\"hello, world\")\n"
"reformatted -\n"
"All done! ✨ 🍰 ✨\n"
"1 file reformatted.\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/the_basics.md:425
msgid ""
"**Tip:** if you need _Black_ to treat stdin input as a file passed directly "
"via the CLI, use `--stdin-filename`. Useful to make sure _Black_ will "
"respect the `--force-exclude` option on some editors that rely on using "
"stdin."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/the_basics.md:429
msgid "You can also pass code as a string using the `--code` option."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/the_basics.md:431
msgid "Writeback and reporting"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/the_basics.md:433
msgid ""
"By default _Black_ reformats the files given and/or found in place. "
"Sometimes you need _Black_ to just tell you what it _would_ do without "
"actually rewriting the Python files."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/the_basics.md:436
msgid ""
"There's two variations to this mode that are independently enabled by their "
"respective flags:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/the_basics.md:439
msgid "`--check` (exit with code 1 if any file would be reformatted)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/the_basics.md:440
msgid "`--diff` (print a diff instead of reformatting files)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/the_basics.md:442
msgid "Both variations can be enabled at once."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/the_basics.md:444
msgid "Output verbosity"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/the_basics.md:446
msgid ""
"_Black_ in general tries to produce the right amount of output, balancing "
"between usefulness and conciseness. By default, _Black_ emits files modified "
"and error messages, plus a short summary."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/the_basics.md:450
msgid ""
"$ black src/\n"
"error: cannot format src/black_primer/cli.py: Cannot parse: 5:6\n"
"    mport asyncio\n"
"         ^\n"
"ParseError: bad input\n"
"reformatted src/black_primer/lib.py\n"
"reformatted src/blackd/__init__.py\n"
"reformatted src/black/__init__.py\n"
"Oh no! 💥 💔 💥\n"
"3 files reformatted, 2 files left unchanged, 1 file failed to reformat.\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/the_basics.md:463
msgid "The `--quiet` and `--verbose` flags control output verbosity."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/the_basics.md:465
msgid "Configuration via a file"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/the_basics.md:467
msgid ""
"_Black_ is able to read project-specific default values for its command line "
"options from a `pyproject.toml` file. This is especially useful for "
"specifying custom `--include` and `--exclude`/`--force-exclude`/`--extend-"
"exclude` patterns for your project."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/the_basics.md:472
msgid ""
"**Pro-tip**: If you're asking yourself \"Do I need to configure anything?\" "
"the answer is \"No\". _Black_ is all about sensible defaults. Applying those "
"defaults will have your code in compliance with many other _Black_ formatted "
"projects."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/the_basics.md:476
msgid "What on Earth is a `pyproject.toml` file?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/the_basics.md:478
msgid ""
"[PEP 518](https://peps.python.org/pep-0518/) defines `pyproject.toml` as a "
"configuration file to store build system requirements for Python projects. "
"With the help of tools like [Poetry](https://python-poetry.org/), [Flit]"
"(https://flit.readthedocs.io/en/latest/), or [Hatch](https://hatch.pypa.io/"
"latest/) it can fully replace the need for `setup.py` and `setup.cfg` files."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/the_basics.md:484
msgid "Where _Black_ looks for the file"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/the_basics.md:486
msgid ""
"By default _Black_ looks for `pyproject.toml` containing a `[tool.black]` "
"section starting from the common base directory of all files and directories "
"passed on the command line. If it's not there, it looks in parent "
"directories. It stops looking when it finds the file, or a `.git` directory, "
"or a `.hg` directory, or the root of the file system, whichever comes first."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/the_basics.md:492
msgid ""
"If you're formatting standard input, _Black_ will look for configuration "
"starting from the current working directory."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/the_basics.md:495
msgid ""
"You can use a \"global\" configuration, stored in a specific location in "
"your home directory. This will be used as a fallback configuration, that is, "
"it will be used if and only if _Black_ doesn't find any configuration as "
"mentioned above. Depending on your operating system, this configuration file "
"should be stored as:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/the_basics.md:500
msgid "Windows: `~\\.black`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/the_basics.md:501
msgid ""
"Unix-like (Linux, MacOS, etc.): `$XDG_CONFIG_HOME/black` (`~/.config/black` "
"if the `XDG_CONFIG_HOME` environment variable is not set)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/the_basics.md:504
msgid ""
"Note that these are paths to the TOML file itself (meaning that they "
"shouldn't be named as `pyproject.toml`), not directories where you store the "
"configuration (i.e., `black`/`.black` is the file to create and add your "
"configuration options to, in the `~/.config/` directory). Here, `~` refers "
"to the path to your home directory. On Windows, this will be something like "
"`C:\\Users\\UserName` and stored in the environment variable `%USERPROFILE%`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/the_basics.md:511
msgid ""
"You can also explicitly specify the path to a particular file that you want "
"with `--config`. In this situation _Black_ will not look for any other file."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/the_basics.md:514
msgid ""
"If you're running with `--verbose`, you will see a message if a file was "
"found and used."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/the_basics.md:516
msgid "Please note `blackd` will not use `pyproject.toml` configuration."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/the_basics.md:518
msgid "Configuration format"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/the_basics.md:520
msgid ""
"As the file extension suggests, `pyproject.toml` is a [TOML](https://github."
"com/toml-lang/toml) file. It contains separate sections for different tools. "
"_Black_ is using the `[tool.black]` section. The option keys are the same as "
"long names of options on the command line."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/the_basics.md:525
msgid ""
"Most command-line options can be configured in `[tool.black]` by using their "
"long name without the leading `--` (for example, `--line-length` becomes "
"`line-length`). Options that cannot be configured in `pyproject.toml` are "
"called out explicitly in the option reference above."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/the_basics.md:530
msgid ""
"Note that you have to use single-quoted strings in TOML for regular "
"expressions. It's the equivalent of r-strings in Python. Multiline strings "
"are treated as verbose regular expressions by Black. Use `[ ]` to denote a "
"significant space character."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/the_basics.md:534
msgid ""
"<details>\n"
"<summary>Example <code>pyproject.toml</code></summary>\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/the_basics.md:537
msgid ""
"[tool.black]\n"
"line-length = 88\n"
"target-version = ['py37']\n"
"include = '\\.pyi?$'\n"
"# 'extend-exclude' excludes files or directories in addition to the "
"defaults\n"
"extend-exclude = '''\n"
"# A regex preceded with ^/ will apply only to files and directories\n"
"# in the root of the project.\n"
"(\n"
"  ^/foo.py    # exclude a file named foo.py in the root of the project\n"
"  | .*_pb2.py  # exclude autogenerated Protocol Buffer files anywhere in the "
"project\n"
")\n"
"'''\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/the_basics.md:553
#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/the_basics.md:585
msgid "</details>\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/the_basics.md:555
msgid ""
"<details>\n"
"<summary>More complete <code>pyproject.toml</code> template</summary>\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/the_basics.md:558
msgid ""
"[tool.black]\n"
"line-length = 88\n"
"target-version = [\"py311\"]\n"
"required-version = \"26\"\n"
"include = '\\.pyi?$'\n"
"\n"
"# Formatting behavior\n"
"skip-string-normalization = false\n"
"skip-magic-trailing-comma = false\n"
"preview = false\n"
"unstable = false\n"
"\n"
"# File collection\n"
"extend-exclude = '''\n"
"(\n"
"  ^/foo.py\n"
"  | .*_pb2.py\n"
")\n"
"'''\n"
"force-exclude = '''\n"
"(\n"
"  ^/generated/\n"
")\n"
"'''\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/the_basics.md:587
msgid "Lookup hierarchy"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/the_basics.md:589
msgid ""
"Command-line options have defaults that you can see in `--help`. A "
"`pyproject.toml` can override those defaults. Finally, options provided by "
"the user on the command line override both."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/the_basics.md:593
msgid ""
"_Black_ will only ever use one `pyproject.toml` file during an entire run. "
"It doesn't look for multiple files, and doesn't compose configuration from "
"different levels of the file hierarchy."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/the_basics.md:597
msgid "Next steps"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/the_basics.md:599
msgid ""
"A good next step would be configuring auto-discovery so `black .` is all you "
"need instead of laborously listing every file or directory. You can get "
"started by heading over to [File collection and discovery](./"
"file_collection_and_discovery.md)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage_and_configuration/the_basics.md:603
msgid ""
"Another good choice would be setting up an [integration with your editor](../"
"integrations/editors.md) of choice or with [pre-commit for source version "
"control](../integrations/source_version_control.md)."
msgstr ""
